            "url": "https://cointelegraph.com/news/trumps-tariffs-lower-bitcoin-miner-price-outside-us?utm_source=rss_feed&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=rss_partner_inbound",
            "summary": "The Trump administration's tariffs are set to decrease US demand for Bitcoin mining rigs, leading manufacturers to seek lower prices in other countries. President Trump imposed \"reciprocal tariffs\" on various nations, affecting major crypto mining machine makers in countries like Thailand, Indonesia, and Malaysia with tariffs of 36%, 32%, and 24% respectively. These tariffs will increase the cost of mining rigs in the US by 22%, potentially making operations financially unsustainable. CEO Jaran Mellerud of Hashlabs Mining predicts that even if the tariffs are reversed, US miners' confidence will remain shaken, impacting long-term planning and investments. The US currently contributes 40% of the Bitcoin network's hashrate, and while the total hashrate is not expected to drop, the US may lose a significant share due to the uncertainty caused by the tariffs. The impact of Trump's tariffs extends beyond crypto markets, with Bitcoin down 4% to $76,470. Ultimately, the tariffs are expected to benefit non-US mining operations, leading to a redistribution of Bitcoin's total hashrate globally.",
            "source_type": "news",
            "headline": "Trump tariffs could decrease US demand for Bitcoin miners, benefiting operations outside US as machine prices outside US could fall. Tariffs imposed by Trump administration on major crypto mining machine makers in Thailand, Indonesia, and Malaysia. Mining rig prices see ~22% increase in US due to tariffs. Mellerud doubts reversal of tariffs would restore US miners' confidence. US accounts for ~40% of Bitcoin network hashrate. Bitcoin price down 4% to $76,470 in 24 hours due to tariffs, now 30% off its all-time high.",
            "tickers": [],
            "is_major": true,
            "beta_headline": null
